00:01:17.010 --> 00:01:20.590
Now let's make this rectangle exactly half of the spring.

00:01:20.590 --> 00:01:22.630
We can have Figma do the math for us.

00:01:22.630 --> 00:01:25.750
The frame is 11152 pixels wide.

00:01:25.750 --> 00:01:27.150
Type 1, 0, 0, 0, 0,

00:01:27.150 --> 00:01:29.020
152 divided by two,

00:01:29.020 --> 00:01:31.420
align it to the right edge like this.

00:01:31.420 --> 00:01:33.385
Do you remember how to create the mask?

00:01:33.385 --> 00:01:36.790
Select both of the layers and in the toolbar above,

00:01:36.790 --> 00:01:40.060
the masking option will appear after you have them selected,

00:01:40.060 --> 00:01:43.060
click on the mask where it's something odd has happened.

00:01:43.060 --> 00:01:46.510
Our image has disappeared and it seems like the rectangle is being maxed.

00:01:46.510 --> 00:01:48.520
Instead, if you look at the layers panel,

00:01:48.520 --> 00:01:52.540
you'll see that the photo is actually being used as a mask instead of the rectangle.

00:01:52.540 --> 00:01:54.790
But we actually needed to be the opposite.

00:01:54.790 --> 00:01:57.175
This happened because we had the rectangle on the top.

00:01:57.175 --> 00:01:59.780
Figma will use their bottom layer as mask.

00:01:59.780 --> 00:02:02.135
So we need to move that rectangle on the bottom.

00:02:02.135 --> 00:02:06.390
We can do this either by directly dragging the layer or using a shortcut.

00:02:06.430 --> 00:02:09.575
Now when we hit this mask,

00:02:09.575 --> 00:02:11.720
we evolve, have it mask correctly.

00:02:11.720 --> 00:02:14.015
Here's another thing to watch out for when masking.

00:02:14.015 --> 00:02:16.985
If you are applying masks to all objects on the frame,

00:02:16.985 --> 00:02:20.075
then Figma doesn't create a mask group in the layers panel.

00:02:20.075 --> 00:02:23.510
What this means is that after you add more elements of the frame,

00:02:23.510 --> 00:02:25.700
they will be living under that mask.

00:02:25.700 --> 00:02:28.310
So you'll encounter an odd behavior where you

00:02:28.310 --> 00:02:31.490
try to look for something but it has disappeared for no apparent reason.

00:02:31.490 --> 00:02:32.720
In moments like this, always,

00:02:32.720 --> 00:02:34.175
always check your layers panel.

00:02:34.175 --> 00:02:38.135
It usually holds the clues for any weird behavior you experience.

00:02:38.135 --> 00:02:41.540
If you look here, you'll see that mask isn't part of a group.

00:02:41.540 --> 00:02:43.085
It just sitting on the frame.

00:02:43.085 --> 00:02:45.950
That means it will mask everything that goes on the frame.

00:02:45.950 --> 00:02:48.320
That arrow clearly indicates that to fix it,

00:02:48.320 --> 00:02:51.125
just select the mask and the image that you're masking.

00:02:51.125 --> 00:02:55.260
Right-click and click Group Selection.

00:02:56.320 --> 00:03:00.650
This way mask only worse to within the group and not outside of it.

00:03:00.650 --> 00:03:02.255
Now that we've got that figured out,

00:03:02.255 --> 00:03:04.430
select the image inside the mass group,

