00:05:02.890 --> 00:05:05.330
Okay, Now for the soft crop,

00:05:05.330 --> 00:05:06.770
this is quite simple as well.

00:05:06.770 --> 00:05:12.470
What we need to do is to put a white fading rectangle on the edge of the image.

00:05:12.470 --> 00:05:15.905
So it smoothens out that final edge,

00:05:15.905 --> 00:05:17.600
left edge of the photo.

00:05:17.600 --> 00:05:21.480
This is done using a gradient fill, draw a rectangle.

00:05:22.570 --> 00:05:29.540
Go to the fill of this rectangle and on the strap down Option change solid to Linear,

00:05:29.540 --> 00:05:32.300
Linear, Radial, angular and Diamond.

00:05:32.300 --> 00:05:34.460
These are all gradient fields for some reason,

00:05:34.460 --> 00:05:37.895
Figma decided to save space and dropped the word gradient from it.

00:05:37.895 --> 00:05:39.890
After you change it to linear,

00:05:39.890 --> 00:05:42.860
you'll notice that the fill of the rectangle starts from

00:05:42.860 --> 00:05:46.190
one color on top and feeds to transparent color on the bottom.

00:05:46.190 --> 00:05:47.810
We want this to be white color.

00:05:47.810 --> 00:05:48.980
Inside the color picker,

00:05:48.980 --> 00:05:50.480
we have two colors,

00:05:50.480 --> 00:05:52.205
start and the end color.

00:05:52.205 --> 00:05:55.894
We want start color to be white with 100 opacity,

00:05:55.894 --> 00:05:58.070
and the end to be white again,

00:05:58.070 --> 00:06:00.905
but with 0% opacity, meaning transparent.

00:06:00.905 --> 00:06:03.320
This will then create that fading effect.

00:06:03.320 --> 00:06:05.735
This here is the start color on the color map.

00:06:05.735 --> 00:06:09.560
Drag the dot to that top left corner because that's where the white is.

00:06:09.560 --> 00:06:11.825
If you accidentally click on this gradient line,

00:06:11.825 --> 00:06:15.140
it will change the location of where colors start and end.

00:06:15.140 --> 00:06:17.285
Just drag them back to their corners.

00:06:17.285 --> 00:06:20.030
Okay, do the same thing on the end color.

00:06:20.030 --> 00:06:22.850
Now we have a gradient filled with fading white,

00:06:22.850 --> 00:06:24.290
but this is a wrong direction.

00:06:24.290 --> 00:06:29.120
We want it to start from left and fade on the right to change the direction.

00:06:29.120 --> 00:06:31.130
Grab this handle here.

00:06:31.130 --> 00:06:32.690
Be careful not the box.

00:06:32.690 --> 00:06:36.830
You want to grab the line and then drag to anywhere on the left edge.

00:06:36.830 --> 00:06:40.130
What happened here is that we are telling you to start this color from this point

00:06:40.130 --> 00:06:43.790
and then slowly radiated towards the end color.

00:06:43.790 --> 00:06:46.610
Okay, Let's do the same thing for the end color.

00:06:46.610 --> 00:06:49.790
These red lines are guides and indicate the position.

00:06:49.790 --> 00:06:52.895
Vertical red line shows that we are exactly on the border.

00:06:52.895 --> 00:06:55.070
And then middle horizontal line

00:06:55.070 --> 00:06:57.920
indicates that we are right in the center of the rectangle.

00:06:57.920 --> 00:07:00.350
That's exactly where we want to position it.

00:07:00.350 --> 00:07:02.270
Now we position this field.

00:07:02.270 --> 00:07:07.640
Right at the edge of the image where it meets with a white background.

00:07:07.640 --> 00:07:10.205
In there we have our soft crop.

00:07:10.205 --> 00:07:14.570
You can also stretch this gradient fill to make the fade more smooth.

00:07:14.570 --> 00:07:17.450
As you can see, the transition here is a little sharp.

00:07:17.450 --> 00:07:19.370
If you extend the gradient field,

00:07:19.370 --> 00:07:24.140
then it spreads more evenly and makes a transition smoother and more natural.

00:07:24.140 --> 00:07:25.280
Now depending on the image,

00:07:25.280 --> 00:07:26.510
sometimes this will be not,

00:07:26.510 --> 00:07:30.560
but sometimes you will still have a little abrupt transition like this one.

00:07:30.560 --> 00:07:31.880
In cases like this,

00:07:31.880 --> 00:07:34.520
I duplicate the gradient fell two more times.

00:07:34.520 --> 00:07:36.845
Do I have a total of three fields?

00:07:36.845 --> 00:07:38.720
You can see how it already improved,

00:07:38.720 --> 00:07:40.640
but we can still do a little more.

00:07:40.640 --> 00:07:44.105
You can take each rectangle and shrink or extend them,

00:07:44.105 --> 00:07:47.225
basically creating three fields with three different widths.

00:07:47.225 --> 00:07:51.215
This gives you a bit more control on fixing any sharp transitions.

00:07:51.215 --> 00:07:52.460
There is no exact rule here.

00:07:52.460 --> 00:07:55.910
You basically play with their positioning and sizes until you find

00:07:55.910 --> 00:07:59.360
that sweet spot of the transition and the choice of an image matters to her.

00:07:59.360 --> 00:08:02.000
Some images work better than others with white soft crop,

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:04.490
you want to go for an image that has a lighter background.

00:08:04.490 --> 00:08:09.110
For instance, daylight sky in the background makes a good transition on dark backgrounds.

00:08:09.110 --> 00:08:11.165
The white fade isn't as effective.

00:08:11.165 --> 00:08:13.025
You see here it feels unnatural.

00:08:13.025 --> 00:08:17.045
And black background and black fade does much better job here as you can see.

00:08:17.045 --> 00:08:20.870
But the ideal solution on a background like this would be to pick a color from

00:08:20.870 --> 00:08:26.070
